FOR USING THE INTERNET TO MAKE THREATS<br>
<br>
<br>
United States Attorney Richard H. Stephens announced today that Jerry D. Miller, age 25, was sentenced by the Honorable United States District Judge Barefoot Sanders to three years probation with six months of home confinement, following his March guilty plea to one count of using the Internet to make threats, in violation of Title 18, United States Code, Section 875(c). Judge Sanders also ordered that Miller participate in mental health counseling services and refrain from possessing or using a computer while on probation.<br>
<br>
At the time Miller, a resident of Durant, Oklahoma, entered his guilty plea, he acknowledged under oath that during 2000, using the screen name &quot;cen,&quot; he participated in an Internet relay chat room, which was located on the Undernet IRC Network. The Undernet IRC Network (&quot;Undernet&quot;) is a worldwide network of Internet Relay Chat (IRC) servers that are hosted by private citizens or companies at no charge to users, in exchange for the users' agreements to adhere to the service policies and procedures. Internet America Dallas-Fort Worth (&quot;IADFW&quot;) sponsors a server on the Undernet IRC Network which is located in Dallas, Texas.<br>
<br>
Miller admitted that he used Internet Relay Chat (IRC), a communications software application, to communicate with others in the chat room in text. He admitted that he was aware that the chat channel was monitored by IADFW systems operators to ensure that the users complied with policies and procedures. He also knew that a system operator or designated administrator, who he referred to as an &quot;IRC cop,&quot; could ban a user or &quot;g-line&quot; them if they refused to obey the policies and procedures of the chat room. One of the administrators for the Undernet was Travis Haymore who used the screen name &quot;Bonk.&quot;<br>
<br>
Miller participated in the chat room with others who traded hacker exploits and tools in violation of the IADFW policies and procedures. On more than one occasion, Miller and other hackers in the chat room were banned by systems operator Travis Haymore.<br>
<br>
Miller admitted that on or about November 1, 2000, while in the chat room as &quot;cen,&quot; that he typed in the following message:<br>
<br>
&lt;@cen&gt;bonks day is coming<br>
&lt;@cen<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
&lt;@cen&gt; if i evenually [sic] have to fly to VA and take care of it myself<br>
&lt;@cen&gt;i'll slice that fat mother [f--kers] liver out<br>
&lt;@cen&gt;hear my [sic] travis haymore?<br>
&lt;@cen&gt;jerry miller will cut your [f--king] throat<br>
===topic!#linuxsex-&gt; I AM GOING TO KILL TRAVIS HAYMORE WITH THE 45 I KEEP UNDER MY BED–cen (by cen)<br>
. . .<br>
&lt;@cen&gt;i'll [f--king] kill every haymore in VA till I get the right one<br>
<br>
Miller also made profane threats against other Undernet administrators and other individuals, including an FBI agent who was investigating Miller's internet threats.<br>
<br>
Miller also acknowledged that at the time he made the statements above, he knew that they were being transmitted over the Internet, from his home in Durant, Oklahoma. He knew that the IADFW server in Dallas, Texas was used to monitor his statements, and he made the statements above knowing that they were being sent in interstate commerce, including being sent through the IADFW server in Dallas, Texas, in violation of Title 18, United States Code, Section 875(c).<br>
<br>
The hacker group to which Miller belonged was responsible for denial of service attacks on the Undernet Internet Relay Chat network. One of the denial of service attacks, which occurred on October 21, 2000, resulted in the inability of approximately 150 customers to use their accounts, resulting in financial losses. According to the criminal complaint that was filed in this case, it is alleged that Miller's hacker group conspired to initiate denial of service attacks against the Undernet after they were banned from the Undernet for using the server to trade their hacking tools. Investigation into the illegal activities of the hacker group is continuing, and is likely to result in additional charges being filed.<br>
<br>
This case was prosecuted by Assistant United States Attorney Linda C. Groves of the Computer Hacking and Intellectual Property (CHIP) Unit that has been established in the Dallas United States Attorney's Office. This new, highly specialized CHIP Unit is one of ten units throughout the country that focuses on prosecuting a vast range of computer crimes including computer intrusions or &quot;hacking,&quot; copyright and trademark violations, trade secret theft/economic espionage, theft of computer and high tech components, fraud and other internet crimes such as child pornography trafficking and sexual exploitation of children. The CHIP Unit also focuses on cybercrime prevention by working with representatives from local industry to anticipate future trends, identify vulnerabilities and ultimately stop cybercrime before it occurs. <br>
<br>
U.S. Attorney Stephens praised the investigative work conducted by the Federal Bureau of Investigation, which has been at the forefront of cybercrime prosecutions in the nation.<br>
